<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-15T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-15T11:00:00-05:00" n="641" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d641">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.48/589</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MIN1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-15T17:00:00+01:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 15, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 16, 2.50 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>2092. Your circular telegram 767, May 13.<note n="1" xml:id="d641fn1">See
                                footnote 1, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> I am inclined to
                            think that any relief money sent into portions of Russia now occupied by
                            the enemy will not bring any beneficial results to the Allied cause, but
                            on the contrary the non-sending of same would tend to increase the
                            already existing ill-feeling against Germany, the population then basing
                            non-receipt of relief as due to the German occupation.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_MIN1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>